352
00:23:29.170 --> 00:23:36.100
So, this is Tyre, and this the court.

353
00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.900
Here must I kill  King Pericles;

354
00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:58.330
and if I do it not, I am sure to be hanged at home:

355
00:23:58.330 --> 00:24:04.700
'tis dangerous. Well, I perceive

356
00:24:04.700 --> 00:24:08.970
he was a wise fellow, and had good discretion, that,

357
00:24:08.970 --> 00:24:12.670
being bid to ask what he would of the king, desired

358
00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:17.070
he might know none of his secrets: now do I see he

359
00:24:17.070 --> 00:24:21.300
had some reason for't; for if a king bid a man be a

360
00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:24.070
villain, he's bound by the indenture of his oath to

361
00:24:24.070 --> 00:24:28.500
be one! Hush! here come the lords of Tyre.

362
00:24:31.630 --> 00:24:33.300
You shall not need, my fellow peers of Tyre,

363
00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:35.730
Further to question me of your king's departure:

364
00:24:35.730 --> 00:24:38.400
His seal'd commission, left in trust with me,

365
00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:43.330
Doth speak sufficiently he's gone to travel.

366
00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:44.800
How! the king gone!

367
00:24:44.800 --> 00:24:47.500
If further yet you will be satisfied,

368
00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:49.800
Why, as it were unlicensed of your loves,

369
00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:54.030
He would depart, I'll give some light unto you.

370
00:24:54.030 --> 00:24:56.000
Being at Antioch--

371
00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:57.230
What from Antioch?

372
00:24:57.230 --> 00:25:00.070
Royal Antiochus--on what cause I know not--

373
00:25:00.070 --> 00:25:04.100
Took some displeasure at him; at least he judged so:

374
00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:05.770
And doubting lest that he had err'd or sinn'd,

375
00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:08.870
To show his sorrow, he'ld correct himself;

376
00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:11.500
So puts himself unto the shipman's toil,

377
00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:15.600
With whom each minute threatens life or death.

378
00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:17.700
Well, I perceive

379
00:25:17.700 --> 00:25:20.270
I shall not be hang'd now,

380
00:25:20.270 --> 00:25:23.930
But since he's gone, the king's seas must please:

381
00:25:23.930 --> 00:25:28.130
He 'scaped the land, to perish at the sea.

382
00:25:28.130 --> 00:25:34.300
I'll present myself. Peace to the lords of Tyre!

383
00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:36.830
Lord Thaliard from Antiochus is welcome.

384
00:25:36.830 --> 00:25:38.670
From him I come

385
00:25:38.670 --> 00:25:42.030
With message unto princely Pericles;

386
00:25:42.030 --> 00:25:44.530
But since my landing I have understood

387
00:25:44.530 --> 00:25:49.870
Your lord has betook himself to unknown travels,

388
00:25:49.870 --> 00:25:53.600
My message must return from whence it came.

389
00:25:53.600 --> 00:25:54.800
We have no reason to desire it,

390
00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:57.930
Commended to our master, not to us:

391
00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:00.870
Yet, ere you shall depart, this we desire,

392
00:26:00.870 --> 00:26:06.570
As friends to Antioch, we may feast in Tyre.

393
00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:17.300
(â™ª music)

394
00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:48.300
My Dionyza, shall we rest us here,

395
00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:51.800
And by relating tales of others' griefs,

396
00:26:51.800 --> 00:26:54.570
See if 'twill teach us to forget our own?

397
00:26:54.570 --> 00:26:59.130
That were to blow at fire in hope to quench it;

398
00:26:59.130 --> 00:27:01.630
For who digs hills because they do aspire

399
00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:05.830
Throws down one mountain to cast up a higher.

400
00:27:05.830 --> 00:27:11.930
O my distressed lord, even such our griefs are;

401
00:27:11.930 --> 00:27:14.830
Here they're but felt, and seen with mischief's eyes,

402
00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:18.670
But like to groves, being topp'd, they higher rise.

403
00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:20.130
O Dionyza,

404
00:27:20.130 --> 00:27:23.100
Who wanteth food, and will not say he wants it,

405
00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:26.000
Or can conceal his hunger till he famish?

406
00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:29.170
Our tongues and sorrows force us to sound deep

407
00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:33.170
Our woes into the air; our eyes do weep,

408
00:27:33.170 --> 00:27:37.000
Till tongues fetch breath that may proclaim them louder;

409
00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.600
That, if heaven slumber while their creatures want,

410
00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:44.270
They may awake their helps to comfort them.

411
00:27:47.030 --> 00:27:53.730
I'll then discourse our woes, felt several years,

412
00:27:53.730 --> 00:27:58.400
And wanting breath to speak help me with tears.

413
00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:02.300
I'll do my best, sir.

414
00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:06.830
This Tarsus, o'er which I have the government,

415
00:28:06.830 --> 00:28:10.300
A city on whom plenty held full hand,

416
00:28:10.300 --> 00:28:14.470
For riches strew'd herself even in the streets;

417
00:28:14.470 --> 00:28:18.430
Whose towers bore heads so high they kiss'd the clouds,

418
00:28:18.430 --> 00:28:21.230
And strangers ne'er beheld but wondered at;

419
00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:25.000
Whose men and dames so jetted and adorn'd,

420
00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.070
Like one another's glass to trim them by:

421
00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:30.830
Their tables were stored full, to glad the sight,

422
00:28:30.830 --> 00:28:33.700
And not so much to feed on as delight;

423
00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:39.870
All poverty was scorn'd, and pride so great,

424
00:28:39.870 --> 00:28:43.170
The name of help grew odious to repeat.

425
00:28:43.170 --> 00:28:45.470
O, 'tis too true.

426
00:28:45.470 --> 00:28:48.300
But see what heaven can do! By this our change,

427
00:28:48.300 --> 00:28:51.870
These mouths, who but of late, earth, sea, and air,

428
00:28:51.870 --> 00:28:54.030
Were all too little to content and please,

429
00:28:54.030 --> 00:28:56.900
Although they gave their creatures in abundance,

430
00:28:56.900 --> 00:28:58.670
As houses are defiled for want of use,

431
00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:02.200
They are now starved for want of exercise:

432
00:29:02.200 --> 00:29:05.630
Those palates who, not yet two summers younger,

433
00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:09.570
Must have inventions to delight the taste,

434
00:29:09.570 --> 00:29:12.970
Would now be glad of bread, and beg for it:

435
00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:14.930
Those mothers who, to nousle up their babes,

436
00:29:14.930 --> 00:29:18.070
Thought nought too curious, are ready now

437
00:29:18.070 --> 00:29:20.530
To eat those little darlings whom they loved.

438
00:29:20.530 --> 00:29:23.170
So sharp are hunger's teeth, that man and wife

439
00:29:23.170 --> 00:29:27.130
Draw lots who first shall die to lengthen life:

440
00:29:27.130 --> 00:29:30.470
Here stands a lord, and there a lady weeping;

441
00:29:30.470 --> 00:29:33.170
Here many sink, yet those which see them fall

442
00:29:33.170 --> 00:29:38.270
Have scarce strength left to give them burial.

443
00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:39.970
Is not this true?

444
00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:43.470
Our cheeks and hollow eyes do witness it.

445
00:29:43.470 --> 00:29:46.500
O, let those cities that of plenty's cup

446
00:29:46.500 --> 00:29:49.070
And her prosperities so largely taste,

447
00:29:49.070 --> 00:29:57.870
With their superfluous riots, hear these tears!

448
00:29:57.870 --> 00:30:02.400
The misery of Tarsus may be theirs.

449
00:30:06.670 --> 00:30:08.270
Where's the lord governor?

450
00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:09.400
Here.

451
00:30:09.400 --> 00:30:12.300
Speak out thy sorrows which thou bring'st in haste,

452
00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:14.630
For comfort is too far for us to expect.

453
00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:17.270
We have descried, upon our neighbouring shore,

454
00:30:17.270 --> 00:30:21.030
A portly sail of ships make hitherward.

455
00:30:21.030 --> 00:30:22.530
I thought as much.

456
00:30:22.530 --> 00:30:24.730
One sorrow never comes but brings an heir,

457
00:30:24.730 --> 00:30:26.970
That may succeed as his inheritor;

458
00:30:26.970 --> 00:30:30.370
And so in ours: some neighbouring nation,

459
00:30:30.370 --> 00:30:33.270
Taking advantage of our misery,

460
00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:36.970
Hath stuff'd these hollow vessels with their power,

461
00:30:36.970 --> 00:30:40.630
To beat us down, the which are down already;

462
00:30:40.630 --> 00:30:46.800
And make a conquest of unhappy me,

463
00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:49.100
That's the least fear; for, by the semblance

464
00:30:49.100 --> 00:30:53.530
Of their white flags display'd, they bring us peace,

465
00:30:53.530 --> 00:30:57.800
And come to us as favourers, not as foes.

466
00:30:57.800 --> 00:31:00.230
Thou speak'st like him's untutor'd to repeat:

467
00:31:00.230 --> 00:31:03.030
Who makes the fairest show means most deceit.

468
00:31:03.030 --> 00:31:05.770
But bring they what they will and what they can,

469
00:31:05.770 --> 00:31:07.170
What need we fear?

470
00:31:07.170 --> 00:31:12.300
The ground's the lowest, and we are half way there.

471
00:31:12.300 --> 00:31:14.230
Go tell their general we attend him here,

472
00:31:14.230 --> 00:31:16.500
To know for what he comes, and whence he comes,

473
00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:17.730
And what he craves.

474
00:31:17.730 --> 00:31:19.330
I go, my lord.

475
00:31:19.330 --> 00:31:25.000
Welcome is peace, if he on peace consist;

476
00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:29.400
If wars, we are unable to resist.

477
00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:35.800
(â™ª music)

478
00:31:35.800 --> 00:31:40.530
Lord governor, for so we hear you are,

479
00:31:40.530 --> 00:31:42.570
Let not our ships and number of our men

480
00:31:42.570 --> 00:31:46.000
Be like a beacon fired to amaze your eyes.

481
00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.830
We have heard your miseries as far as Tyre,

482
00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:53.900
And seen the desolation of your streets:

483
00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:56.300
Nor come we to add sorrow to your hearts,

484
00:31:56.300 --> 00:31:59.300
But to relieve them of their heavy load;

485
00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:01.130
And these our ships, you happily may think

486
00:32:01.130 --> 00:32:03.470
Are like the Trojan horse was stuff'd within

487
00:32:03.470 --> 00:32:06.470
With bloody veins, expecting overthrow,

488
00:32:06.470 --> 00:32:10.970
Are stored with corn to make your needy bread,

489
00:32:10.970 --> 00:32:14.570
And give them life whom hunger starved half dead.

490
00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:16.800
The gods of Greece protect you!

491
00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:18.700
And we'll pray for you.

492
00:32:20.630 --> 00:32:32.930
Arise, I pray you, rise:

493
00:32:34.800 --> 00:32:39.570
We do not look for reverence, but for love,

494
00:32:39.570 --> 00:32:43.130
And harbourage for ourself, our ships, and men.

495
00:32:43.130 --> 00:32:48.170
The which when any shall not gratify,

496
00:32:48.170 --> 00:32:51.630
Or pay you with unthankfulness in thought,

497
00:32:51.630 --> 00:32:59.630
Be it our wives, our children, or ourselves,

498
00:32:59.630 --> 00:33:04.170
The curse of heaven and men succeed their evils!

499
00:33:04.170 --> 00:33:07.370
Till when,--the which I hope shall ne'er be seen,--

500
00:33:07.370 --> 00:33:13.500
Your grace is welcome to our town and us.

501
00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:16.830
Which welcome we'll accept; feast here awhile,

502
00:33:16.830 --> 00:33:22.600
Until our stars that frown lend us a smile.

503
